>
  <p>The demo is the easy part.</p>
  <p>The harder question is what happens when AI enters real work: client conversations, advisor preparation, service workflows, CRM, case management, data handoffs, approvals, controls, exceptions, and leadership reporting.</p>
  <p>That is where the gap usually appears. The model may be capable. The enterprise may not be ready.</p>

  <blockquote>The hard part is not access to AI. The hard part is changing work without breaking trust.</blockquote>

  <h2>The assistant is not the operating model</h2>
  <p>Most enterprise AI investment has started at the edge of work. People use AI to draft, summarize, search, or prepare. That helps. It does not automatically change the work.</p>
  <p>An advisor may still prepare the same way. A service associate may still follow the same process. A leader may still review the same dashboard. The tool improved. The system of work did not.</p>

  <h2>The real shift is execution</h2>
  <p>Execution means AI enters the workflow with a clear role. It knows what context matters. It knows what action is allowed. It shows the evidence. It hands the work back when judgment, risk, or exception handling is required.</p>
  <p>That is a different problem from tool rollout. It requires decision rights, trusted data, controls, adoption, monitoring, and business ownership.</p>

  <h2>Data decides whether AI can act</h2>
  <p>The problem is rarely that data does not exist. The problem is that the right data is not trusted at the moment the work needs to move.</p>
  <p>AI cannot fix unclear ownership, conflicting sources, stale context, or evidence no one is willing to stand behind.</p>

  <h2>The executive question</h2>
  <p>The useful question is no longer “Can AI do this?” The useful question is, “Can the enterprise change the work safely enough to make it matter?”</p>
  <p>That is the leadership challenge. AI will keep moving. The advantage will go to organizations that can change workflow, data, governance, and decision-making without losing trust.</p>
